
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dh_autoreconf_clean` baraye paak kardan file-haye sakhte shode az `autoreconf` dar bazi-sazi pakage Debian estefade mishavad. In dastoor mohem ast chon ke file-haye sakhte shode momken ast ba version-haye mokhtalef `autoconf` va `automake` sazgar nabashand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 Heech gozine khas baraye karbar nist, chon in dastoor bishtar dar poshte parde va dar script-haye bazi-sazi estefade mishavad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dh_autoreconf_clean

    🔹 Dastoor ra be tanhaee ejra konid ta file-haye be ja mande az `autoreconf` ra paak konad. Obdatan, in dastoor dar file `debian/rules` qable az `dh_clean` seda zade mishavad.

    $ debian/rules clean

    🔹 Ejraye ghsmate `clean` dar file `debian/rules`. In kar ham `dh_autoreconf_clean` va ham digar dastoorat pak-sazi ra ejra mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    Ba estefade az `dh_autoreconf_clean`, اطمینان حاصل کنید ke pakage-haye Debian-e shoma az no build hastand va problem-haye sazgar ba version-haye mokhtalef `autoconf` va `automake` ra nadarand.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dh_autoreconf_clean` command is used to clean up files generated by `autoreconf` during Debian package builds. It's essential because generated files might not be compatible across different versions of `autoconf` and `automake`.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 There are typically no user-facing options, as this command is mainly used behind the scenes in build scripts.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dh_autoreconf_clean

    🔹 Run the command standalone to clean up leftover `autoreconf` generated files. Typically, this command is invoked in `debian/rules` before `dh_clean`.

    $ debian/rules clean

    🔹 Run the `clean` target in `debian/rules`. This will execute `dh_autoreconf_clean` along with other cleanup commands.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    By using `dh_autoreconf_clean`, you ensure that your Debian packages are built cleanly and avoid compatibility issues with different versions of `autoconf` and `automake`.
